PROSPER LOAN DATA ANALYSIS

By Emily Hazelton

This report explores loan data provided by the online lender Prosper (a tidy dataset that Udacity prepared for student projects). The data spans from November, 2005 to March, 2014. Any column headers listed as “current” was current as of March 11, 2014, when the dataset was last pulled.

Univariate Plots Section

There are 113,937 observations in the full dataset with 81 variables. I have picked 12 variables for this exploration, as detailed below. I’ve also shown a sample of the first 6 rows for each variable.

Questions:

  • What are the most popular categories for the loan status?

It looks like the most commonly occurring loan statuses are current, completed, and charged off.

Questions:

  • What proportion of loans are charged off?
  • What factors predict that the borrower will go into loan delinquency?
  • What is the distribution of loan amounts?

The default bin sizes here for loan amount makes it hard to see anything meaningful.

Unsurprisingly, loan amounts cluster around the 500 or 1,000 marks.

Most frequent loan amounts:

  • $4,000
  • $15,000
  • $10,000
  • $5,000

Question:

  • How long do loan terms last?

The loan terms in this data set fall into three bins: 12, 36, or 60 months, with 36 months being the most common. Since there are only 3 discrete values, I am going to change the vector type from integer to a factor, so I can graph it categorically in the bivariate section. I would also find the length-of-loan variable easier to interpret as 1, 3, or 5 years.

Questions:

  • What is the average credit score for borrowers? I want to create an average from credit_score_lower and credit_score_uppers so that I have one variable to use for analysis.

Yes, over 50,000 observaions seems sufficient to reasonably trust any conclusions drawn from this dataset. From here forward, I will be looking at this more specific dataset, named closed_loans in the R environment.

The above graph visually shows the counts of Chargedoff vs Completed loans. Completed loans are loans where the borrower completely paid off the original loan amount. 24.0 percent of closed loans are in the Chargedoff category.

Questions: * How many 1, 3, and 5 year loans fall within the closed status? * What is the spread of loan amounts within closed_loans?

Three-year loans are still the most common. In relation to the 3-year loans, there are proportionally more 1-year loans and less 5-year loans as compared to the full Prosper loan dataset.

The spread for closed loans leans more towards smaller loans than the full Prosper set. Perhaps consumers were asking for smaller loans historically, or perhaps Prosper was more conservative in how much funding they would award to consumers as they refined their profit predictions – I don’t have a way to find the answer to that question with the dataset that I have.

Most popular loans:

  • $4,000
  • $5,000
  • $3,000
  • $2,000

With these smaller loan sizes, this smaller profit makes more sense. This data was also collected over the span of the recession, so interest rates would have been very low during that time. That also helps explain the low ROI per loan.

Question:

  • What type of return does the bank expect to make on its lending?

This graph shows what the bank estimated the return to be when they funded the loan. It looks like there is a spread between 0.025 and 0.2 (or 2.5 to 20 percent of return on investment).

Questions:

  • What does actual return look like?

Most loans are profitable for the bank, with more common profits ranging from just breaking even (.0) to 50 percent (.5). There is a strange peak above 0.5, and I’m not sure why that is. If I were working for Prosper, I would definitely look at that. But for the sake of this project, I’m going to move past it.

The formula I used for acual return was bank_profit_current divided by loan_amount.

Question:

  • Is Prosper’s model for predicting profit conservative? Or pretty accurate?

  • What is the distribution of debt-to-income ratio for borrowers?

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

I decided to focus my investigation on loans that have been completed or charged off. There are 50,066 observations that meet this criteria.

  • In the closed_loans dataset, there are 38,074 completed loans and 11,992 charged off loans. 24.0 percent of closed Prosper loans were charged off.
  • Prosper loans are one, three, or five years in duration.
  • The most common credit score for borrowers is between 665 and 725.
  • The average profit per loan is $21.12.
  • The loan amount for at least half of Prosper loans in the closed_loan dataset is equal to or less than $5,000.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

For the rest of this analysis, I would like to focus on what variables can help predict actual_return.

I anticipate that the following variables will have the strongest correlation to actual_return:

  • credit_score_average
  • loan_term_years
  • loan_amount

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I will also explore what covariation exists between actual_return and the following variables. I expect less of a correlation amongst these, but want to check to see if any of these have a higher impact than I would expect:

  • employment_status
  • debt_income_ratio
  • employment_duration_years
  • stated_annual_income

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Yes. I transformed several variables into forms that I feel will be more concise for visualization purposes:

  • credit_score_average: calculated from credit_score_lower and credit_score_upper
  • loan_term_years: loan_term_months divided by 12; also converted to a factor
  • employment_duration_years: employment_duration_months divided by 12
  • stated_annual_income: stated_income_monthly multiplied by 12

I wanted one variable to use for credit score, rather than two. And I find it easier to interpret the data when the loan term, employment duration, and income is stated annually rather than monthly.

Now, I have the following variables to move into the bivariate analysis:

It looks like there may be a negative correlation between annual income and estimated return. My primary factor of interest is estimated_return (displayed across the bottom). Some of the strong correlations – between principal paid and loan_amount or actual_return and bank_profit_current – are obvious because the variables do have an explicit relationship.

Question:

  • How is actual_return related to credit_score_average?
## Warning: Removed 539 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

It doesn’t look like I will be able to use credit score in a predictive model for actual return. I really expected more of a correlation. It does look like individuals who have a score over 800 are a very safe bet for investment. Perhaps the overplotting on this graph is hiding a trend that is there.

Question:

  • Would a grouped boxplot show a better trend?
## Warning: Removed 464 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

It looks like the median return is above 0 for all ranges except those centering at 450 and below. And the peak in the median return occurs at a credit score of 570.

With this graph, it looks like there is a pattern in the relationship between credit score and return. Those with poor or fair credit scores are bringing the highest rate of return. This is likely because these individuals pay higher interest rates.

It looks like three-year loans have the highest median percentage of return. And it looks like Prosper is losing the most money on five-year loans. In fact, almost half of five-year loans are losing money.

Here we see the effects of overplotting within the bands of most common loan amounts. It does look like the return falls much more above 0, which is good for Prosper. Let’s take a look at this with a boxplot grouping to see where the medians lie by $1,000 bins.

## Warning: Removed 17 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

Return is above 0 for all loan amounts. There really is no evidence of variation in the loan amount changing the ROI.

Question:

  • How does debt-to-income-ratio impact return?
## Warning: Removed 3975 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

The relationship between bank profit and stated monthly income doesn’t seem to have a linear pattern, but an outlier is seriously skewing the x scale of that graph, so I’m going to zoom in.

## Warning: Removed 3975 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

It seems as though a higher debt_income_ratio (DIR) is related to a higher profit. There seem to be some tiers to the data, althought it is still hard to see due to overplotting. But it seems that there are jumps in the level of profit at both 0.25 and 0.5 marks for DIR.

Question:

  • How does employment status impact return?

These are some strange tiers, with redundancy. My guess is that the option set changed at some point in data collection. For example “employed” was later changed to two options – “part-time” and “full-time.”

The plot shows density, so that the count of each category doesn’t scew the graph. The graph shows a proportion for each category.

It is surprising to me that those with an employment_status of ‘employed’ bring Prosper a lower actual_return. However, I know that some of the data collection criteria changed in 2009, based on the data dictionary. I don’t know exactly when the employment_status optionset would have changed. But if ‘Employed’ is from an earlier date, it’s not a good comparison (because there are many environmental differences that could make a difference if the data was collected during two different time periods).

Let’s zoom in to the peak area of this graph.

It’s interesting that retired and part-time individuals seem to peak at a higher actual_return rate. Perhaps it is a similar phenomenon to why Prosper makes a better return for those with lower credit scores – perhaps these individuals are assigned a higher interest rate.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

Loan term covaried with actual return. The return for one-year loans was mostly positive, but not much more than 0. Three-year loans brought in the highest return. Five-year loans were responsible for the most lost in return.

Credit score also varied with actual return. Credit scores centering right under 600 actually brought the highest level of return.

Otherwise, I really didn’t find any other patterns of covariation.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

I didn’t find any areas of covariation in the non-central variables that I did explore.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Credit score and actual return. Which makes sense, since the industry has spent years perfecting a single indicator that will tell the bank how trustworthy you are as an investment.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This plot shows that most loans that have a positive return on investment. The average return for a funded loan is 2.8 percent.

##   mean_return_percent median_return_percent
## 1             2.78961              12.62516

Plot Two

Description Two

Prosper gives out loans that are one, three, or five years in duration. Almost 90 percent of loans are provided with a three year term. The median return for these loans is 13.6 percent. However, the average return is only 4 percent. Negative outliers are bringing the average lower than the median.

The median return for one-year loans is 5.9 percent, with average profit at 3.8 percent. And the median return for five-year loans is 5.8 percent, with average profit at negative 13.4 percent. As can be seen in the graph above, the second quartile for five-year loans falls into a negative return. The five-year loan category is not profitable for Prosper.

Reflection

What was challenging:

  • I was surprised that I didn’t uncover a clear linear model or strong pattern between actual_return and the various factors I investigated. I was frustrated about that. Staying motivated on this project was difficult, because I didn’t feel like I uncovered any key insights.
  • I didn’t get a chance to build a model because there were no linear relationships that emerged. Perhaps a more complex model could work, but I am currently not educated on those, so it was beyond the scope of my experience at this point in time.

What went well:

  • I learned a lot about ggplot, using R studio, and how to approach the EDA process. One example of a process technique that I learned is to do a thorough exploration about variation (i.e. univariate analysis) and then move on to explore covariation (bivariate and mutlivariate analysis).
  • I enjoyed the creativity and curiosity that the EDA process requires. I was able to practice using a wide range of graph types in ggplot.
  • I am excited to take this skillset to analyzing other datasets.

Further areas for investigation:

  • How does early payoff impact actual return? That is, if a borrower pays their loan off early, I anticipate that actual return would be lower.
  • Analyze the difference between estimated return and actual return. Focus on areas where the bank anticipated profit but lost money. Is there a factor that their predictions should also take into account? Or is that just part of the risk of the lending process (e.g. the exploration would not uncover additional factors to create better predictive models of expected profit)?
